<div id="review_973399644" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/973399644" />
    <a title="7jane" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/28266234-7jane"><img alt="7jane" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1391265302p2/28266234.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/973399644?book_show_action=true">Jun 21, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="7jane" class="user" itemprop="url" name="7jane" href="/user/show/28266234-7jane">7jane</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780060652951" href="/book/show/479798.The_Great_Divorce">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/28266234-7jane?shelf=religion">religion</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer973399644" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5538099560495098430">There are many reviews of this book, so I just make a few sentences of my own observations here:<br/>- reading the &quot;tvtropes&quot; page of this book does help<br/>- the story isn&apos;t long, and comfortably easy and quick a read<br/>- preface is essential to read before the main text<br/>- the story gives a nod to many writers Lewis had read (starting with being inspired by William Blake, of course); one early scifi short story is mentioned as an influence, but no one has been able to indentify it by name<br/>- the description o</span>
  <span id="freeText5538099560495098430" style="display:none">There are many reviews of this book, so I just make a few sentences of my own observations here:<br />- reading the "tvtropes" page of this book does help<br />- the story isn't long, and comfortably easy and quick a read<br />- preface is essential to read before the main text<br />- the story gives a nod to many writers Lewis had read (starting with being inspired by William Blake, of course); one early scifi short story is mentioned as an influence, but no one has been able to indentify it by name<br />- the description of Hell is not 'hot and fiery' but 'wet and permanently at evening twilight'; people hate each other so much that they live wide apart (one reason why the it keeps spreading further<br />- Heaven is different for those who live there and those who come there by bus from Hell: the latter can't move easily around as every blade of grass hurts - but they hurt only as long as they're not willing to change<br />- and many are so stubbornly clinging to something (possessing someone they love, to 'what people might think', to believing they were good when in truth they weren't etc. etc.) that they won't, so they run back to the bus to go back down to Hell<br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[- the way the story ended showing it was a dream had in the study during WWII was both fitting and amusing; and why shouldn't some truths come to us this way, even if it's partly symbolic? <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />So I found this book enjoyable, thought-provoking and inspiring, not gloomy. I will certainly read it again.</span>
